Hierarchical Dirichlet Regression Model for Benthic Cover in the Abrolhos Bank

Pamela M. Chiroque-Solano

Sciences Department at University of Lisboa, CE3C, Portugal
Institute of Biology and SAGE-COPPE, Federal University of Rio de Janeiro, Brazil

This work was done in collaboration with Mariana S. Sá and Larissa M. Martins.

Joint Statistical Meetings virtual conference

11st of August, 2021

Motivation

  • Understanding the local patterns for the composition data of benthic coral reef dynamic in the Abrolhos bank;

  • Investigating the heterogeneity of the multivariate response under different sites.

Historical facts

Objectives

  • To disassemble the composition via the stochastic representation for Dirichlet random vectors;

  • To model the variability effects by sites including a hierarchical structure;

  • To achieve flexibility with the proposed model, so that it can be useful in many settings.

Proposal

  • Combined approach: Compositional data model from (Maier 2014) and multilevel structure from (Gelman and Hill 2006);

  • Filtered information through the decomposition of the Dirichlet distribution parameter into two components: level and precision;

  • This decomposition allows us to obtain a flexible proposal.

Notation

(Wang, Tian, and Tang 2011; Maier 2014)

  • \(y_{ic} \in (0,1)\): The proportion of coverage at observation \(i\) of component \(c\).

  • \(\sum_{c=1}^{C}y_{ic} = 1\): Constraint

Assumptions

  • \(\mathbf y \sim \mathcal{D}(\mathbf \alpha)\) on \(C>2\)-dimensional hyperplane or closed simplex \(\mathbb{T}_{C}(1)\).

  • \(\alpha_c > 0\)

  • The Dirichlet’s probability density function:

\[\begin{eqnarray} f(\mathbf y)&=& \frac{\Gamma(\alpha_{1}+\ldots+\alpha_{c})}{\prod _{c=1}^{C} \Gamma(\alpha_{c})} \prod _{c=1}^{C} y_{c}^{ \alpha_{c}-1}, \quad \sum_{c=1}^{C}y_c=1. \end{eqnarray}\]

Hierarchical Dirichlet regression under the Bayesian approach

Based on the alternative parametrization (Maier 2014; Holger and Sennhenn-Reulen 2018);

  • \(\mathbf Y_l \sim D(\mathbf\mu_l,\phi_l)\) with parameter \(\alpha_{cl} = \mu_{cl}\phi_l\)

  • \(\mu_{cl}\) : level term

  • \(\phi_{l}\) : precision term

\[\begin{eqnarray*} \mu_{icl} = E(Y_{icl}\mid \mathbf x_i)&=&\frac{\exp( \mathbf x_i^{\prime}\mathbf\beta_{cl})}{\sum_{d=1}^{C}\exp(\mathbf x_i^{\prime}\mathbf\beta_{dl})}, \quad \mu_{icl}\in(0,1) \\ \nonumber \phi_{il} &=& \exp(\mathbf z_i^{\prime}\theta_{l}), \quad \theta_{l} \in \mathbb{R} \nonumber \\ \beta_{cl} &=& \beta_{c}+ \epsilon_{\beta_{l}} \nonumber\\ \theta_{l} &=& \theta+ \epsilon_{\theta_{l}} \end{eqnarray*}\]

Reference component

  • \(\alpha_{cl} = \mu_{cl}\phi_l\)

  • \(c^\star\) reference component should be chosen and \(\mathbf\beta_{c^\star}\) is set to zero;

  • For the \(c^\star\) the expectation vector is given by

\[ \mu_{ic^\star l} = \frac{1}{\sum_{d=1}^{C} \mu_{idl}} \]

  • The reference dimension is chosen based on exploratory disassembling of components.

Inference procedure

  • Let \(\Theta =(\mathbf\beta,\mathbf\phi)\) be the vector of parameters
  • Proper independent prior distribution for the parametric vector \(\mathbf{\Theta}\) are Normal with zero mean and precision \(1/K\) for all effects of the model.

  • The posterior distribution \[\begin{eqnarray}\label{posterior} \pi(\mathbf\Theta \mid \mathbf y) \propto L(\mathbf\Theta\mid \mathbf y)\prod_{l}^{L}\pi(\phi_l)\prod_{c}^{C}\pi(\beta_{cl}) \end{eqnarray}\]

  • Likelihood \(L(\mathbf\Theta \mid {\mathbf y} )=\prod_{i=1}^{n}\prod_{l=1}^{L}f(\mathbf y_{il} \mid \mathbf\Theta)\).

  • The joint posterior distribution does not have a known closed form;

  • Sampling from the posterior distribution is done by Markov chain Monte Carlo (MCMC) via the Stan software.

Aplication: Abrolhos bank

  • Reef Structures (Teixeira, Chiroque-Solano, and al. 2021)

Conclusion

  • The proposed model quantifies the heterocedasticity through precision effects via hierachical structures by site;

  • The method is flexible;

  • The reference component has been chosen using objective criteria;

  • The proposal allows to obtain adequate predictions.
